Node selector
Pod chooses node by label.
Simple and exact.

Affinity / anti-affinity
Pod expresses rules or preferences.
More advanced and smarter.

Taints / tolerations
Node blocks pods unless they are allowed.
Best for isolation and reservation.


====================

Taints and Tolerations

===
LAB 1 — TAINTS & TOLERATIONS (Hands-on)

Goal
Control where pods are scheduled.

Step 1: Check your nodes
oc get nodes --show-labels

Step 2: Add a taint to a node

Pick one worker node (example):
oc adm taint nodes ip-10-0-65-134.ec2.internal key=infra:NoSchedule

Meaning:
No pod can schedule here
Unless it has matching toleration

Verify taint
oc describe node ip-10-0-65-134.ec2.internal | grep Taints

Step 3: Create a pod WITHOUT toleration
apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata:
  name: test-no-toleration
spec:
  containers:
  - name: nginx
    image: nginx
oc apply -f pod.yaml

Result:
oc get pod

Status: Pending

Reason:
oc describe pod test-no-toleration

You’ll see:
node(s) had taint {key=infra: NoSchedule}

Step 4: Add toleration (FIX)
apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata:
  name: test-with-toleration
spec:
  tolerations:
  - key: "key"
    operator: "Equal"
    value: "infra"
    effect: "NoSchedule"
  containers:
  - name: nginx
    image: nginx

oc apply -f pod.yaml


Concept	Meaning
Taint	Node says “don’t come here”
Toleration	Pod says “I can handle it”

Remove taints
oc adm taint nodes ip-10-0-17-110.ec2.internal key-



