LAB 2 — INFRA NODE (VERY IMPORTANT in OpenShift)

What is Infra Node?

Dedicated node for:

Router pods (ingress)
Registry
Monitoring
Logging

Keeps app workloads separate

Step 1: Label node as infra
oc label node ip-10-0-65-134.ec2.internal node-role.kubernetes.io/infra=""

Step 2: Add taint (IMPORTANT)
oc adm taint nodes ip-10-0-65-134.ec2.internal node-role.kubernetes.io/infra=true:NoSchedule

Step 3: Move router to infra node
oc patch ingresscontroller.operator default \
  -n openshift-ingress-operator \
  --type=merge \
  -p '{
    "spec": {
      "nodePlacement": {
        "nodeSelector": {
          "matchLabels": {
            "node-role.kubernetes.io/infra": ""
          }
        },
        "tolerations": [
          {
            "key": "node-role.kubernetes.io/infra",
            "operator": "Exists",
            "effect": "NoSchedule"
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  }'

Verify
oc get pods -n openshift-ingress -o wide

Router pods should move to infra node ✅

Node Type	Purpose
Worker	Application pods
Infra	Platform services
Master	Control plane

===

LAB 3 — DISABLING A NODE

Scenario:
Maintenance / issue / upgrade

Step 1: Cordon node (disable scheduling)
oc adm cordon ip-10-0-65-134.ec2.internal

Node still running pods
But no new pods

Step 2: Drain node (evacuate pods)
oc adm drain ip-10-0-65-134.ec2.internal --ignore-daemonsets --delete-emptydir-data

Moves pods to other nodes

Verify
oc get pods -o wide

Step 3: Uncordon (enable back)
oc adm uncordon ip-10-0-65-134.ec2.internal

===

Important Notes (REAL WORLD)
Action	Impact
cordon	safe
drain	disruptive
taint	permanent control

Difference:

Feature	Use
Node Selector	Simple placement
Affinity	Advanced rules
Taint	Block scheduling
Toleration	Allow exception


