#Day 4 - NFS PVC PV

Create NFS Server (on EC2 / VM)

Run this on a Linux machine (your jump server or separate EC2)

Step 1: Install NFS
sudo yum install -y nfs-utils

Step 2: Create shared directory
sudo mkdir -p /nfs-share
sudo chmod 777 /nfs-share

Step 3: Configure export
sudo vi /etc/exports

Add:

/nfs-share *(rw,sync,no_root_squash,no_subtree_check)

Step 4: Start NFS service
sudo systemctl enable --now nfs-server

Step 5: Allow firewall (if needed)
sudo systemctl stop firewalld

Step 6: Verify
showmount -e

Output should show:
/nfs-share *

PART 2 — Create Persistent Volume (PV)

Replace <NFS_SERVER_IP> with your EC2 private IP

apiVersion: v1
kind: PersistentVolume
metadata:
  name: nfs-pv
spec:
  capacity:
    storage: 5Gi
  accessModes:
    - ReadWriteMany
  nfs:
    path: /nfs-share
    server: <NFS_SERVER_IP>
  persistentVolumeReclaimPolicy: Retain
oc apply -f pv.yaml

PART 3 — Create Persistent Volume Claim (PVC)

apiVersion: v1
kind: PersistentVolumeClaim
metadata:
  name: nfs-pvc
spec:
  accessModes:
    - ReadWriteMany
  resources:
    requests:
      storage: 1Gi
oc apply -f pvc.yaml

Verify binding
oc get pv
oc get pvc

STATUS should be:
Bound

PART 4 — Use PVC in Pod

apiVersion: v1
kind: Pod
metadata:
  name: nfs-pod
spec:
  containers:
  - name: app
    image: nginx
    volumeMounts:
    - mountPath: /usr/share/nginx/html
      name: nfs-storage
  volumes:
  - name: nfs-storage
    persistentVolumeClaim:
      claimName: nfs-pvc
oc apply -f pod.yaml

PART 5 — Test Persistence

Step 1: Write data
oc exec -it nfs-pod -- bash
echo "Hello from NFS" > /usr/share/nginx/html/index.html
exit

Step 2: Expose service
oc expose pod nfs-pod --port=80
oc expose svc nfs-pod

Open route → should show:
Hello from NFS

Step 3: Delete pod
oc delete pod nfs-pod

Recreate:

oc apply -f pod.yaml

Step 4: Verify again
Data still exists


